A new science
In this summer, an unusual conference took place in Paris. There, researchers gathered to think about the necessity of a new science that could be just as revolutionary as Einstein's insights a hundred years ago.
The majority of scientists assume that the fundamental questions of science have been answered.
Considering the major challenges, the view is that there is only little left to discover.
The remaining questions can be divided into three groups: Firstly, the great unsolved puzzles of science (such as the unification of gravity and electricity in a theory), the exploration of which requires enormous investments and the infrastructure of the First World. Secondly, data collection, referring to work related to archaeological excavations and biological/genetic studies, and thirdly, problems whose solution is to be based on scientific foundations, such as the fight against AIDS or global warming.
Moreover, many people believe that the only difficult part of the work would be to utilize already known natural laws with the help of new technologies for the benefit of humanity.
Who could deny that?
Today's models do function, after all.
A growing group of scientists, however, point to phenomena that cannot be explained so well with today's theories.
These problems do occur more and more frequently, but they are also skillfully circumvented because the science to explain them simply does not exist.
This missing science would describe processes and the emergence of entire systems.
In the individual scientific disciplines, the knowledge is somewhat well secured.
Physics, at least the part with which we as normal people are confronted, is well researched.
Chemistry and biochemistry also stand on solid foundations – there are a few things in our body that we still don't understand, but it can be assumed that the basic mechanisms of interaction between cells and molecules are known.
Furthermore, there are also the new social sciences that deal with humans and societies.
In every one of these areas – physics, biochemistry, and social science – the theories are solid and mostly also uncontested.
Each discipline has its own language and its own mechanisms.
In the rarest of cases is a scientist an expert in more than one field, because these worlds and languages are so vastly different.
This means that we cannot find an answer to complex questions that require the involvement of multiple disciplines.
One thinks, for example, of the brain.
This complex organ consists of molecules whose interaction is based on the foundations of physics. The information mediated in this process is transferred based on the laws of electricity.
There is also a system of specialized cells that communicate through the exchange of chemical substances and thereby also transfer information.
When interacting with two brains, a new level comes into play: Here, information exchange occurs through language, signs, and concepts.
On each level, it's about the exchange of information, and there are suitable theories that explain the processes on each individual level.
Information is also exchanged between the individual levels, but there is no science that could even in outline explain this information exchange.
To compensate for this lack, some scientists have tried to redefine the instrumentation for explaining processes within a level, in order to then apply it on another level.
These attempts then lead to something like a „language“ on a cellular level and „energy“ behind organized societies.
Occasionally, this „transplantation“ of explanation patterns works quite well, but the underlying problem is not solved thereby: What is the nature of the information exchanged between the individual levels and how is it transmitted?
Now, almost all systems in this world consist of such levels.
And in all cases, there is this shameful lack of knowledge about how the overall system functions.
The group of interdisciplinary researchers who gathered in Paris has informally formed under the name "Foundations of Information Science".
The researchers come from various countries and fields of research and have been working together in a decentralized manner for eight years.
Alongside researchers from relevant disciplines, art theorists, psychiatrists, language experts, and philosophers are also participating in the discussion.
The majority of the group relies on this "transplantation strategy", where the scientific foundations of one level are adapted and supplemented to be applied to another.
Others, however, consider a completely new approach to be necessary.
According to their view, many scientific norms are the product of historical accidents and new ways of thinking are needed.
If the FIS group is lucky, new radical approaches will emerge from scientists who currently have no access to the infrastructure of the First World.
Completely free thinking is an underestimated factor.
Nearly all activities that take place under the banner of "science" have, similar to their counterparts in the world of economics, developed an institutional character.
One believes that the developing countries must build up similar resources as the industrial countries. This could, however, stifle creative thinking.
Many young scientists are currently undergoing a revolution and many of these – sometimes revolutionary – ideas come from laboratories and research centers that are not associated with the major institutions.
The most well-thought-out approaches in the field of mathematical algorithms came twenty years ago from the Soviet Union, where there was a lack of computing capacity at every corner and end.
The most brilliant and, in the truest sense of the word, world-changing insights in the field of physics in recent decades did not come as expected from the known innovation centers, but from Budapest.
In Iran, there is a tradition of architecture that helped cognitive scientists to important insights.
And the most radical new ideas in the field of the second generation of artificial intelligence (so-called "autonomous agents") now come from Prague.
The most creative scientific achievements went into history.
When Einstein expanded physics with a new way of thinking, the identity of space and time changed. The FIS conference in July was the unannounced beginning of an attempt to redefine the universe in this way.
Those gaps were identified for which explanations are needed.
Other researchers from innovative regions will still be added to this group in order to then identify those problems that could be solved if this new science were developed in the future, or discovered, as one wants to put it.

